# Bilingual UI (Korean + English)

This site supports **Korean and English** via the language toggle. Any new page, template change, or user-visible string is incomplete if only Korean is added.

## When this applies

- New features, pages, forms, alerts, buttons, labels, tooltips
- Modifications to existing UI (do not add KO-only copy in touched areas)
- Server redirect error messages shown on pages (use error **codes** + bilingual template text, not Korean-only query strings)

Admin-only screens: still prefer KO/EN for consistency; deep admin copy may stay KO if explicitly scoped out.

## Implementation patterns (use what fits)

### 1. Jinja templates — `nav-ko` / `nav-en`

```html
<span class="nav-ko">입금 신청</span>
<span class="nav-en" style="display:none">Submit claim</span>
```

Markdown from SiteSettings: provide both `*_ko` and `*_en` keys; show each in the matching `nav-*` block (fallback EN → KO if EN empty).

### 2. Confirm dialogs — `data-app-confirm-i18n`

```html
<form data-app-confirm-i18n="offers.confirmMatch">
```

Add matching keys in `app/static/js/i18n.js` under both `en:` and `ko:`.

### 3. Dynamic JS strings — `i18n.js`

Add `ko` and `en` entries; use `window.t('key')` or dual DOM nodes updated on language change.

### 4. API / service errors — error codes

Return stable codes (e.g. `match_blocked`, `pending_claim_exists`), not Korean sentences in URLs. Map codes to bilingual alerts in templates (`partials/billing_err_alert.html` pattern).

### 5. Emails / SMS

When adding transactional notifications, consider EN copy or document as follow-up if only KO is implemented in the same PR.

## Checklist before finishing UI work

- [ ] Every new visible string has KO and EN (or `i18n.js` key in both locales)
- [ ] Language toggle shows sensible text (no empty EN blocks)
- [ ] Form confirms use `data-app-confirm-i18n`, not hardcoded Korean-only `data-app-confirm`
